Media notes: Fledgling that escaped from nest, now in grass.
Observation Details: When I checked in on the nest...  The first fledgling had fled the nest.  I located it on the ground in grass below the nest.  Mama Mourning Dove was positioned on top of it keeping it warm.  In the nest, the second fledgling was still there, alone at the moment.  I left and came back in about 15 minutes.  At that point, Mama Mourning Dove had returned to the nest and was sitting on the fledgling in the nest.  The fledgling that had escaped the nest was alone in the grass.  I'm glad I don't see cats in this area often.  Timeline...  I first noted the nest with eggs on July 11. I noted egg shells on the ground below the nest on July 16. The first glimpse I got of the baby doves was on July 23. The first bird left the nest on July 24.

Observation Details: Timeline of this breeding.   February 27. Two doves seen nest building. Gathering dried grass and other nesting material.   March 2. Nest complete and mama dove was sitting on it, apparently incubating eggs.   March 17. Egg shells noted on the ground below the nest. Presumably they hatched on or shortly before March 17.   March 25. Two nestlings visually confirmed in nest.   March 31. Two fledglings first left the nest, flying to the ground. They stayed close to the nest, not leaving the yard for several days.

Observation Details: I heard a noise and saw a fledgling fall from a tree and immediately fly away.  Then it's nest mate fell and landed in the same place, but instead of flying away, it just fluttered around, drawing the attention of a neighborhood cat. I didn't want the cat to get the baby bird, so I grabbed it before the cat got to it and waited for the cat to leave before releasing the bird. While I had the fledgling in hand, I noticed that its tail looked longer, wider, and more square than I expect for a mourning dove. I think it was a hybrid with part Eurasian collared  dove. I know both species are common in the area. I never got a good enough look at the parents or sibling to be sure what kind of dove they were, but I think if anything I had seen more collared than mourning doves in the immediate area around that time. I heard both species' calls fairly often, but was not aware of the nest before the fledglings came out.

Observation Details: Male came in and fed the chick for ~2 minutes. At first the chick seemed to peck at the bill of the male but then it got its while bill inside the mouth of the male to feed. The female was close behind and as the male walked away on the branch, he seemed to briefly be feeding the female. The female then took a turn feeding the fledgeling before moving up to another branch. The rain started to come down and the fledgeling followed the female up to the higher branch and attempted to nestle into the downy feathers on the chest and belly of the female. Observation Details: As quickly as I removed the twigs from my car, she would put more on there. I even brought a large clay pot near the car and started placing the twigs in there, hoping she would use that instead. No luck. Eventually, I turned to the Internet to see if I could find some ideas about how to stop this nest building on my car. The best idea was to put strips of aluminum foil under the wiper blades. It worked! No more nest. But I feel bad, because she didn't use the pot I put there, either. I'm hoping she found another, more suitable, place for her nest.

Observation Details: We watched this pair of Mourning Doves constructing a nest on our porch light. The (presumed) female was perched on the nest, and the male would bring a stick, landing on the porch railing for a bit. He would then fly and land on top of the female's back, usually passing it to her, and she would stick it underneath her into the nest. The male tried putting a few into the nest, but it seems it was less successful getting them to stay. The female stayed on top of the work-in-progress nest for about 6 hours, only leaving for brief periods, until about 1:30pm, when thry both left and were done constructing for the day.  4/7 update: this pair continued building the nest on 4/6, but they only worked on it for about 1-2 hours. On 4/7 we did not see them visit at all. The location on the light is not that sturdy, but the nest has held so far.

Observation Details: Long Description: Mourning Doves were seen towards the end of the walk (approx. 1pm). They were on the wet ground near a brook, hidden in brambles. They seemed unafraid of us and wouldn't fly away even as we approached them. They didn't appear injured, but we were worried since they seemed a bit lackadaisical. We were able to get relatively close (approx. ten feet away) to observe their features in detail. The Mourning Doves had black bars on the outside of their coverts. Their tail feathers were very long and their bellies were an off-white. Their grayish blue heads clearly stood out from their taupe brown bodies. The two doves were preening and spreading their wings as if to dry them since it was very wet and boggy. Neither of them made any noises and blended into their surroundings, we only noticed them when they started to move away from us. It was easy to see their thin small beaks and the light eye ring as well as the black stripes on their primary feathers. The Mourning Doves were staying together which made us think they were mates. As soon as one started moving in a specific direction, the other would follow. When we left, they waddled off in the other direction.
